  (772,238,116,'a:2:{s:5:\"tizer\";s:161:\"<p>A multilingual dictionary that allows users to enter lexical units, search for their meaning, display respective variants of translation in set languages.</p>\";s:4:\"text\";s:771:\"<h1>ProductX</h1>\r\n<h2>Category</h2>\r\n<p>Mobile.</p>\r\n<h2>Distinctive Features of the Project</h2>\r\n<p>A multilingual dictionary that allows users to enter lexical units, search for their meaning, display respective variants of translation in set languages.</p>\r\n<h2>Tests Conducted</h2>\r\n<p>Functional testing (system, regression, configuration, usability).</p>\r\n<h2>Tools</h2>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Planning: MS Project, MS Word;</li>\r\n<li>Test cases: MS Excel;</li>\r\n<li>Change management: IBM Rational ClearQuest.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h2>Artifacts</h2>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Functional test plan;</li>\r\n<li>Functional test cases;</li>\r\n<li>Software quality reports.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h2>Project Team</h2>\r\n<p>Test manager, 1 specialist in functional testing.</p>\r\n<h2>Effort</h2>\r\n<p>~ 320 hours.</p>\";}'),
  (773,239,114,'600 hours'),
  (774,239,113,'MobiTee'),
  (775,239,115,'2 specialists'),
  (776,239,116,'a:2:{s:5:\"tizer\";s:81:\"<p>Mobile golf-assistant designed for Symbian and Windows Mobile smartphones.</p>\";s:4:\"text\";s:800:\"<h1>MobiTee</h1>\r\n<div class=\"LeftImg\"><img src=\"/uploaded/image/screens/MobiTee.jpg\" height=\"176px\" width=\"232px\" /></div>\r\n<h2>Category</h2>\r\n<p>Mobile.</p>\r\n<h2>Distinctive Features of the Project</h2>\r\n<p>Mobile golf-assistant designed for Symbian and Windows Mobile smartphones.</p>\r\n<h2>Tests Conducted</h2>\r\n<p>Functional testing (system, regression, configuration, integration, usability).</p>\r\n<h2>Tools</h2>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Planning: MS Project, MS Word;</li>\r\n<li>Test cases: MS Excel;</li>\r\n<li>Change management: IBM Rational ClearQuest.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h2>Artifacts</h2>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Functional test plan;</li>\r\n<li>Check lists;</li>\r\n<li>Software quality reports.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h2>Project Team</h2>\r\n<p>Test manager, 1 specialist in functional testing.</p>\r\n<h2>Effort</h2>\r\n<p>~ 600 hours.</p>\";}'),
  (777,240,114,'2 000 hours'),
  (778,240,113,'Free Tracking'),
  (779,240,115,'2 specialists'),
  (780,240,116,'a:2:{s:5:\"tizer\";s:119:\"<p>Free Tracking is an application which allows its users to track the location and movement of registered objects.</p>\";s:4:\"text\";s:1765:\"<h1>Free Tracking</h1>\r\n<div class=\"LeftImg\"><img width=\"369px\" height=\"176px\" src=\"/uploaded/image/screens/FreeTracking.jpg\" /></div>\r\n<h2>Category</h2>\r\n<p>Mobile, GPS.</p>\r\n<h2>Distinctive Features of the Project</h2>\r\n<p>Free Tracking is an application which allows its users to track the location and movement of registered objects. Object position is defined by a mobile device embedded GPS module and then transmitted to the server via GPRS connection.</p>\r\n<p>The system incorporates the following modules:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>A mobile client installed on a target mobile device to define the current position and send the data to the server at fixed time intervals, as well as notifying if the user has closed the application. The observer may be notified of application shutdown or refusal of tracking by the object under observation by means of a short text message or email. </li>\r\n<li> A web-system, whose functions include administration, user management, report generation, user coordinates mapping, signalling when the object leaves the set area, setting data storage period from 1 to 6 months. </li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>Support for Symbian S60 FP1 &amp; FP2, Windows Mobile 5.0, 6.0 and 6.1 (Pocket PC and smartphones).</p>\r\n<h2>Tests Conducted</h2>\r\n<p>Functional testing (system, regression, configuration, integration, installation, usability).</p>\r\n<h2>Tools</h2>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Planning: MS Project, MS Word;</li>\r\n<li>Test cases: MS Excel;</li>\r\n<li>Change management: IBM Rational ClearQuest.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h2>Artifacts</h2>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Functional test plan;</li>\r\n<li>Functional test cases;</li>\r\n<li>Software quality reports.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h2>Project Team</h2>\r\n<p>Test manager, 1 specialist in functional testing.</p>\r\n<h2>Effort</h2>\r\n<p>~ 2,000 hours.</p>\";}'),
  (781,241,114,'80 hours'),
  (782,241,113,'Buddy-tracker'),
  (783,241,115,'2 specialists'),
  (784,241,116,'a:2:{s:5:\"tizer\";s:89:\"<p>The application allows its users to track the location of the registered vehicles.</p>\";s:4:\"text\";s:1103:\"<h1>Buddy-tracker</h1>\r\n<h2>Category</h2>\r\n<p>Mobile, GPS.</p>\r\n<h2>Distinctive Features of the Project</h2>\r\n<p>The application allows its users to track the location of the registered vehicles.</p>\r\n<p>Key system features include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>System login, server connection;</li>\r\n<li>Tracked vehicles data viewing (car number, location address, ignition status, coordinates);</li>\r\n<li>Reporting on vehicle location (in ascending order by distance to the vehicle).</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>The application keeps the GPRS connection active at all times and sends data updates at fixed time intervals.  Support for Symbian S60 FP1.</p>\r\n<h2>Tests Conducted</h2>\r\n<p>Functional testing (system, regression).</p>\r\n<h2>Tools</h2>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Planning: MS Project, MS Word;</li>\r\n<li>Check list: MS Excel;</li>\r\n<li>Change management: IBM Rational ClearQuest.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h2>Artifacts</h2>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Functional test plan;</li>\r\n<li>Check list;</li>\r\n<li>Software quality reports.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h2>Project Team</h2>\r\n<p>Test manager, 1 specialist in functional testing.</p>\r\n<h2>Effort</h2>\r\n<p>~ 80 hours.</p>\";}'),
  (785,242,114,'~ 920 hours'),
  (786,242,113,'Strela-Servise Order Management System'),
  (787,242,115,'2 specialists'),
  (788,242,116,'a:2:{s:5:\"tizer\";s:88:\"<p>The project was aimed at testing of the 444 Taxi Service order management system.</p>\";s:4:\"text\";s:993:\"<h1>Strela-Servise Order Management System</h1>\r\n<h2>Category</h2>\r\n<p>Mobile, ECM.</p>\r\n<h2>Distinctive Features of the Project</h2>\r\n<p>The project was aimed at testing of the 444 Taxi Service order management system.</p>\r\n<p>The system incorporates:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>A database server;</li>\r\n<li>A mobile client for taxi drivers;</li>\r\n<li>A desktop application for registration and forwarding of customer calls for service operators.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>Support for Symbian S60 9.1.</p>\r\n<h2>Tests Conducted</h2>\r\n<p>Functional testing (system, regression, configuration, usability)</p>\r\n<h2>Tools</h2>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Planning: MS Project, MS Word;</li>\r\n<li>Test cases: MS Excel;</li>\r\n<li>Change management: IBM Rational ClearQuest.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h2>Artifacts</h2>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Functional test plan;</li>\r\n<li>Functional test cases;</li>\r\n<li>Software quality reports.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h2>Project Team</h2>\r\n<p>Test manager, 1 specialist in functional testing.</p>\r\n<h2>Effort</h2>\r\n<p>~ 920 hours.</p>\";}'),
  (789,243,114,'510 hours'),
  (790,243,113,'M.Video'),
  (791,243,115,'2 specialists'),
  (792,243,116,'a:2:{s:5:\"tizer\";s:177:\"<p>M.Video is an infotainment resource which allows its users to get M.Video product information, perform search, learn about product discounts and available points of sale.</p>\";s:4:\"text\";s:1476:\"<h1>M.Video</h1>\r\n<div class=\"LeftImg\"><img src=\"/uploaded/image/screens/mvideo.jpg\" height=\"176px\" width=\"307px\" /></div>\r\n<h2>Category</h2>\r\n<p>Mobile, e-Business.</p>\r\n<h2>Distinctive Features of the Project</h2>\r\n<p>M.Video is an infotainment resource which allows its users to get M.Video product information, perform search, learn about product discounts and available points of sale.</p>\r\n<p>Main system features include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>GPRS or Wi-Fi connection to M.Video server;</li>\r\n<li>Access to existing catalogues: news, special offers, gifts, shops for the selected city;</li>\r\n<li>Storage of updated data in a local database;</li>\r\n<li>Access to images and goods descriptions;</li>\r\n<li>Generation of a shop list for a selected city, shop location details (tips on how to get to a shop, opening hours);</li>\r\n<li>Location map for a selected point of sales, access to Google Maps;</li>\r\n<li>Access to the selected phone help desk.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>iPhone support.</p>\r\n<h2>Tests Conducted</h2>\r\n<p>Functional testing (system, regression, usability).</p>\r\n<h2>Tools</h2>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Planning: MS Project, MS Word;</li>\r\n<li>Test cases: MS Excel;</li>\r\n<li>Change management: IBM Rational ClearQuest.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h2>Artifacts</h2>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Functional test plan;</li>\r\n<li>Functional test cases;</li>\r\n<li>Software quality reports.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h2>Project Team</h2>\r\n<p>Test manager, 1 specialist in functional testing.</p>\r\n<h2>Effort</h2>\r\n<p>~ 510 hours.</p>\";}'),
  (793,244,114,'920 hours'),
  (794,244,113,'Skyguard Mobile'),
  (795,244,115,'2 specialists'),
  (796,244,116,'a:2:{s:5:\"tizer\";s:84:\"<p>The application has been designed for the Skyguard rescue service in London .</p>\";s:4:\"text\";s:1385:\"<h1>Skyguard Mobile</h1>\r\n<div class=\"LeftImg\"><img src=\"/uploaded/image/screens/skyguard.jpg\" height=\"177px\" width=\"358px\" /></div>\r\n<h2>Category</h2>\r\n<p>Mobile.</p>\r\n<h2>Distinctive Features of the Project</h2>\r\n<p>The application has been designed for the Skyguard rescue service in London .</p>\r\n<p>Main system function is to run quick search and provide assistance to persons with serious medical conditions unable to call for ambulance on their own and to emergency victims.</p>\r\n<p>Key system features include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Sending user GPS coordinates to the rescue service at a fixed time interval via SMS or GPRS connection;</li>\r\n<li>Emergency call for medical aid to the rescue centre;</li>\r\n<li>&bull;\tLoudspeaker activation for reporting user condition.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>Support for Symbian S60 FP1 &amp; FP2, Windows Mobile 5.0, 6.0 and 6.1 (Pocket PC), BlackBerry.</p>\r\n<h2>Tests Conducted</h2>\r\n<p>Functional testing (system, regression, configuration).</p>\r\n<h2>Tools</h2>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Planning: MS Project, MS Word;</li>\r\n<li>Test cases: MS Excel;</li>\r\n<li>Change management: IBM Rational ClearQuest.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h2>Artifacts</h2>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Functional test plan;</li>\r\n<li>Functional test cases;</li>\r\n<li>Software quality reports.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h2>Project Team</h2>\r\n<p>Test manager, 1 specialist in functional testing.</p>\r\n<h2>Effort</h2>\r\n<p>~ 920 hours.</p>\";}'),
  (797,245,114,'750 hours'),
  (798,245,113,'Solovat Fabric Keyboard'),
  (799,245,115,'2 specialists'),
  (800,245,116,'a:2:{s:5:\"tizer\";s:111:\"<p>The project included testing of a set of flexible keyboard drivers for Bluetooth enabled mobile devices.</p>\";s:4:\"text\";s:1042:\"<h1>Solovat Fabric Keyboard</h1>\r\n<h2>Category</h2>\r\n<p>Mobile, Embedded.</p>\r\n<h2>Distinctive Features of the Project</h2>\r\n<p>The project included testing of a set of flexible keyboard drivers for Bluetooth enabled mobile devices.</p>\r\n<p>The project was aimed to replace smartphone keyboard in order to facilitate and speed up typing of text messages and letters, work with the Internet and mobile office and other applications.</p>\r\n<p>Support for Symbian S60 2nd edition, 3rd edition, UIQ 2.1, UIQ 3; Palm 5.0.</p>\r\n<h2>Tests Conducted</h2>\r\n<p>Functional testing (system, regression, configuration, integration, usability).</p>\r\n<h2>Tools</h2>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Planning: MS Project, MS Word;</li>\r\n<li>Test cases: MS Excel;</li>\r\n<li>Change management: IBM Rational ClearQuest;</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h2>Artifacts</h2>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Functional test plan;</li>\r\n<li>Functional test cases;</li>\r\n<li>Software quality reports.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h2>Project Team</h2>\r\n<p>Test manager, 1 specialist in functional testing.</p>\r\n<h2>Effort</h2>\r\n<p>~ 750 hours.</p>\";}'),
  (801,246,114,'~ 200 hours'),
  (802,246,113,'Introduction of Automated Software Testing for an Enterprise'),
  (803,246,115,'3 specialists'),
  (804,246,116,'a:2:{s:5:\"tizer\";s:56:\"<p>The Customer is a major Russian state enterprise.</p>\";s:4:\"text\";s:1199:\"<h1>Introduction of Automated Software Testing for an Enterprise</h1>\r\n<h2>Category</h2>\r\n<p>Consulting / Training</p>\r\n<h2>Customer</h2>\r\n<p>The Customer is a major Russian state enterprise.</p>\r\n<h2>Work Conducted</h2>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Design and teaching of training courses in functional and automated software testing;</li>\r\n<li>IBM Rational Robot functional test automation;</li>\r\n<li>Training of customer specialists in terms of maintenance and development of scripts based on the designed framework.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h2>Tools</h2>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Test automation tool: IBM Rational Robot;</li>\r\n<li>Design of test cases, test management: IBM Rational TestManager;</li>\r\n<li>Change management: IBM Rational ClearQuest.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h2>Artifacts</h2>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Slides, document samples as consistent with the course syllabi;</li>\r\n<li>Automated functional test cases;</li>\r\n<li>Automated testing framework;</li>\r\n<li>Automated test scripts.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h2>Project Team</h2>\r\n<p>1 project manager, 1 teacher for the Introduction into Functional Software Testing course and the Introduction into Automated Software Testing course, 1 specialist in test automation.</p>\r\n<h2>Effort</h2>\r\n<p>~ 200 hours.</p>\";}'),
  (805,247,117,'a:2:{s:5:\"tizer\";s:140:\"<p><strong>Test plan &ndash;</strong> a document describing the scope, approach, resources, and schedule of intended testing activities.</p>\";s:4:\"text\";s:721:\"<h1>Test Plan</h1>\r\n<p>A document describing the scope, approach, resources, and schedule of intended testing activities.</p>\r\n<p>It is generally divided into the following sections:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Tasks and objectives of testing;</li>\r\n<li>Extent of testing;</li>\r\n<li>Resources;</li>\r\n<li>Test platform;</li>\r\n<li>Testing strategy, general software testing milestones;</li>\r\n<li>Work schedule and estimated effort;</li>\r\n<li>Change management;</li>\r\n<li>Delivery of new software versions;</li>\r\n<li>Test start and test stop criteria;</li>\r\n<li>Test results delivery;</li>\r\n<li>Risk assessment.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>The document is most often presented in the MS Word format supplemented by a work schedule in MS Project.</p>\";}'),
  (806,248,117,'a:2:{s:5:\"tizer\";s:0:\"\";s:4:\"text\";s:350:\"<p><strong>Test scenario (test suite)</strong>&nbsp;&ndash; a document set of test cases classified by testing types, functions and other parameters. A test scenario may be presented as an MS Office (Excel, Word) document or take the format of an automated software test management system file (HP Test Director, IBM Rational Test Manager, etc.).</p>\";}'),
  (807,249,117,'a:2:{s:5:\"tizer\";s:238:\"<p><strong>Test case</strong> &ndash; a document containing a detailed description of a test for one or more system features with indicated specific data needed to start the test and keep it running as well as predicting test results.</p>\";s:4:\"text\";s:916:\"<h1>Test Case</h1>\r\n<p>A document containing a detailed description of a test for one or more system features with indicated specific data needed to start the test and keep it running as well as predicting test results.</p>\r\n<p>Test cases can include GUI testing checklists, system checks and checks for input data integrity, field execution behavior, correct input value and correct data storage, business logic, unauthorized access data change and data deletion protection, etc.</p>\r\n<p>As a general rule, test cases are based on the following structure:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Unique identifier;</li>\r\n<li>Name;</li>\r\n<li>Preconditions;</li>\r\n<li>Test steps;</li>\r\n<li>Expected result;</li>\r\n<li>Test result.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>A test case may be presented as an MS Office (Excel, Word) document or take the format of an automated software test management system file (HP Test Director, IBM Rational Test Manager, etc.).</p>\";}'),
  (808,250,117,'a:2:{s:5:\"tizer\";s:265:\"<p><strong>Data-driven testing</strong> &ndash; data-driven method is used in software test automation and represents the type of testing in which the action of a test case is parameterized by externally defined data values, maintained as a file or spreadsheet.</p>\";s:4:\"text\";s:2457:\"<h1>Data-Driven Testing</h1>\r\n<p>Data-driven testing method is used in software test automation and represents the type of testing in which the action of a test case is parameterized by externally defined data values, maintained as a file or spreadsheet.</p>\r\n<p>Databases can be set up as ODBS resources, Csv or Xls files, etc. This framework uses variables both for input and output check values &ndash; a test script generally encodes app navigation, data source reading, and test logging.</p>\r\n<p>Consequently, script logic is also data dependent. Let us consider data-driven testing in actual practice. Suppose, there is a task in login page testing.</p>\r\n<p>This requires automation of three simple test cases:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Correct (database stored) login and password entry;</li>\r\n<li>Incorrect (lacking in database) login and password entry;</li>\r\n<li>Invalid (data not compliant with data validation conditions) login and password entry.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>Essentially, the three test cases correspond to the same action but with different data and different expected results. Thus, when using a data-driven approach one script and three data pools will suffice.</p>\r\n<p>Data pools can be presented in any format, as a rule, it is a key-value pair. This significantly reduces costs for development of new test cases as well as for maintenance of already existing ones. Undoubtedly, the most effect of data-driven approach is achieved in entry form testing, since one management script can check almost any form with any data.</p>\r\n<p>Main characteristics of data-driven approach include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Script data is stored in external files / databases;</li>\r\n<li>The same case uses different data, which is a compulsory condition. One can often see that all data is outside scripts; meanwhile virtually every test case is absolutely unique in terms of its code;</li>\r\n<li>Reusable data pools.  \r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Reusable data;</li>\r\n<li>Simple test case development;</li>\r\n<li>Higher efficiency as opposed to mere record-replay wherein one test script automates a number of test cases.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n<p>Advantages of data-driven approach:</p>\r\n<h2>Disadvantages of data-driven approach</h2>\r\n<p>Each new test (even if it is only slightly different from the existing one) requires a separate script, which in effect means duplication of code leading to increase in maintenance costs,  the same code must be maintained in multiple areas.</p>\r\n</ul>\";}'),
  (809,251,117,'a:2:{s:5:\"tizer\";s:253:\"<p><strong>Keyword-driven testing</strong> &ndash; this type of testing is also known as table-driven or action-word testing; it represents a common technique in automated functional testing and takes two stages: framework design and implementation.</p>\";s:4:\"text\";s:2706:\"<h1>Keyword-Driven Testing</h1>\r\n<p>Keyword-driven testing, which is also known as table-driven or action-word testing, represents a common technique in automated functional testing and takes two stages: framework design and implementation.</p>\r\n<h2>Framework design stage</h2>\r\n<p>Framework development stage involves creating application object maps and a set of keywords for testing. For example, a simple keyword (one action for one object) is entering a username in a text field.</p>\r\n<table class=\"NormalTable\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td class=\"Bold\">Object</td>\r\n<td class=\"Bold\">Action</td>\r\n<td class=\"Bold\">Data</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"border: 0px;\">Textfield (username)</td>\r\n<td style=\"border: 0px;\">Enter text</td>\r\n<td style=\"border: 0px;\">username</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<p>The example of a complex keyword (keywords combination in a complex module) is a system login.</p>\r\n<table class=\"NormalTable\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td class=\"Bold\">Object</td>\r\n<td class=\"Bold\">Action</td>\r\n<td class=\"Bold\">Data</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"border: 0px;\">Textfield (domain)</td>\r\n<td style=\"border: 0px;\">Enter text</td>\r\n<td style=\"border: 0px;\">domain</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"border: 0px;\">Textfield (username)</td>\r\n<td style=\"border: 0px;\">Enter text</td>\r\n<td style=\"border: 0px;\">username</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"border: 0px;\">Textfield (password)</td>\r\n<td style=\"border: 0px;\">Enter text</td>\r\n<td style=\"border: 0px;\">password</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"border: 0px;\">Button (login)</td>\r\n<td style=\"border: 0px;\">Click</td>\r\n<td style=\"border: 0px;\">One left click</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<h2>Implementation Stage</h2>\r\n<p>The implementation stage varies according to the framework or tool used. In most cases test automation specialists implement such keywords as check, enter, click, etc.</p>\r\n<p>Test cases designed by specialists in manual software testing or test designers are based on the keywords that had been defined and developed during the planning stage. In the course of testing a driver checks up for keywords and executes corresponding code.</p>\r\n<h2>Advantages of approach</h2>\r\n<p>Even though keyword-driven approach requires a lengthier planning stage and preparation time before the actual start of test cases design as opposed to other test automation methodologies, it adds to the efficiency of test design  and maintenance stage in the long run ensuring fail-safe test structure and minimum update costs.</p>\r\n<p>The more abstract keywords are used, the less complex is their administration and the smoother is the support stage. The module structure of keyword-driven tests allows creating new tests over already designed modules.</p>\";}'),
  (810,252,118,'1. Introduction of Software Test Automation at the Project Level'),
  (811,252,119,'Alexey Rakitsky'),
  (812,252,120,'a:2:{s:5:\"tizer\";s:205:\"<p>The article presents tips on the possibly smoothest introduction of test automation procedures at the project level for those software manufacturing companies where they are largely out of practice.</p>\";s:4:\"text\";s:7866:\"<h1>Introduction of Software Test Automation at the Project Level</h1>\r\n<p>Alexey Rakitsky, Leading Specialist in Functional and Load Automated Software Testing at Qulix QA.</p>\r\n<p>Target Audience: project managers, IT department managers, specialists interested in adopting and improving test automation practices.</p>\r\n<p>The article presents tips on the possibly smoothest introduction of test automation procedures at the project level for those software manufacturing companies where they are largely out of practice.</p>\r\n<p>Since there is a growing interest in test automation tools and introduction of test automation processes into development projects, the demand for respective training courses and consulting services is rising. That test automation offers a whole range of definite advantages when implemented into a well-balanced and fine-tuned process of software development is beyond question.</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>You are interested in test automation for your projects but there are no specialists of the required qualification in your company?</li>\r\n<li>How painful might the implementation of test automation be in terms of your project or department?</li>\r\n<li>What kind of efficiency and advantages may be expected of test automation?</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>These and lots of other questions flash across the mind of those Qulix QA customers who intend to adopt test automation into their projects. Prior to thinking about the introduction of test automation you should check if the QA process in your projects is fine-tuned, documented and runs like a clock. Remember that adoption of test automation is no tribute to fashion but a task aimed at transmitting your project quality assurance to a principally new level. The goal is to improve the efficiency of project testing, not to get one more headache.</p>\r\n<p>The second step is hiring specialists to quickly and professionally help you start the process of test automation. Of course, you can try implementing the practice using your own effort, but without experienced specialists this process is likely to take a lot of time, go by trial and error, exceed the planned budget, and finally put you off employing any automated testing practices.</p>\r\n<p>Innovative methods of test automation offer the possibility to minimize consulting services while reaping more benefit from cooperation with consulting firms and successfully developing this practice in your company.</p>\r\n<p>In case of from scratch test automation implementation we normally recommend that a framework based on a keyword-driven approach principle should be developed along with running a training course thus enabling your specialists to update the framework and expand automated test coverage. For the present moment KeyWord Driven frameworks offer the most technologically advanced solution as to the price/quality/efficiency correlation.</p>\r\n<p>The advantages of such a framework include:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Maximum reuse of code: substantially, there is a single script that manages all implementation process;</li>\r\n<li>The technology does not exclude Data Driven methods which gives it all advantages of the Data Driven approach;</li>\r\n<li>All actions are compiled in Excel data tables or may be presented in any other format specified by the customer;</li>\r\n<li>All user interface objects are stored in external files;</li>\r\n<li>Additional description of all test cases and test suites is provided in external files (normally in Excel format) for easy start-up options management;</li>\r\n<li>The framework allows maximum flexibility: it is easy to add, delete, and edit existing test cases and test suites which requires no extra skills other than framework operation;</li>\r\n<li>Adding new actions as well as changing the existing ones requires no complex operations &ndash; it&rsquo;s enough to write a new function thus smoothly and painlessly extending the framework;</li>\r\n<li>When switching to a different test automation tool minimum of code is subject to revision, test cases remain as they are.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>This is a cure-all solution for a number of test departments, for the requirements for specialist qualification get considerably lower, once the development of framework and a training course in framework operation have taken place &ndash; it is sufficient to have MS Excel skills.</p>\r\n<h2>How to adopt test automation</h2>\r\n<p>A rule of thumb states that the process should go through the following phases:</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li>Analysing a set of tasks and software development technologies employed by the customer. The analysis provides means for selection of the best test automation tool (paid or free). The scheduled tasks make the backbone for the implementation plan, essential process documentation, and any adjustments to the training course syllabus, whereas practice drills depend on the selected test automation tool.</li>\r\n<li>The focal point of the second phase is the course named Introduction into Automated Software Testing. The course covers all crucial theoretical points as to the process, structure and methods of test automation. Course participants pick up skills in tool management, do practical tasks in functional test script development, learn to correctly create test cases and incorporate them into automated test suites, design core libraries for framework creation and script running.</li>\r\n<li>The concluding phase is all about putting the acquired knowledge into practice. This is the time when trainees supervised by the tutors plan the degree of automated test coverage, develop the framework, perform automation of the stated set of system functions, activate mechanisms of script run and result collection inside of a working project.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p>Once the practice of test automation has been implemented into the manufacturing process the customer should get:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>An infrastructure that is completely ready for further development of test automation inside of a project;</li>\r\n<li>Functional script package covering the stated set of functions with the specified test thoroughness;</li>\r\n<li>Trained specialists capable of independent further development of test automation inside of a given project;</li>\r\n<li>Schedule of test automation activities;</li>\r\n<li>Description of the framework and scripts for the software solution in whose development process test automation was implemented.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>An estimated time frame for the project:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Implementation task analysis: ~ 1 - 2 weeks;</li>\r\n<li>Training (depending on the syllabus): ~ 4 &ndash; 10 business days;</li>\r\n<li>Implementation into an active project (depending on the scheduled scope of work): ~ 3 weeks &ndash; 1,5 weeks.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>With Qulix QA you will get even more benefits, such as:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Transparent and easy-to-understand results reporting and logging system; All start-up logs can be stored in one folder; it is possible to create a results view engine listing results according to the application version number;</li>\r\n<li>Easy script start-up: it takes only one BAT file to run a batch (batches);</li>\r\n<li>Easy sitemap maintenance to ensure minimum cost of update after GUI has been changed;</li>\r\n<li>Complete document package on the created test automation system;</li>\r\n<li>Easy creation of new test cases and test suites will ensure minimum cost of test coverage extension and require no additional skills.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h2>Company Profile</h2>\r\n<p>Qulix QA (<a target=\"_blank\" href=\"http://www.qa.qulix.com\">www.qa.qulix.com</a>) specialises in providing flexible, adaptable and speedy services in independent software testing as well as consulting about QA activities for IT projects. The Company was founded in 2000 and currently operates as a subsidiary of Qulix Group (<a target=\"_blank\" href=\"http://www.qulix.com\">www.qulix.com</a>).</p>\";}'),
  (813,253,118,'2. A Three Page Novel about the Intricacies of Project Management'),
  (814,253,119,'Alexander Sliborsky'),
  (815,253,120,'a:2:{s:5:\"tizer\";s:435:\"<p>Knowledge is power! It is truly so. If you want to be on a roll you have to be well grounded. Modern reality forces us to constantly search for ways of self-improvement, to digest loads of information. However moving with the times and managing to read through all the materials and absorb tons of information is somewhat problematic &ndash; there is a lot to do at work and a pile of regular household chores to handle at home.</p>\";s:4:\"text\";s:15611:\"<h1>A Three Page Novel about the Intricacies of Project Management</h1>\r\n<p>Alexander Sliborsky, Director of Microsoft Technologies Department, Qulix Group.</p>\r\n<p>Knowledge is power! It is truly so. If you want to be on a roll you have to be well grounded. Modern reality forces us to constantly search for ways of self-improvement, to digest loads of information. However moving with the times and managing to read through all the materials and absorb tons of information is somewhat problematic &ndash;  there is a lot to do at work and a pile of regular household chores to handle at home.</p>\r\n<p>As a matter of fact, this article is addressed to those still looking to educate themselves but feeling extremely pressed for time. I am delighted to bring to your attention a review of an excellent book The Deadline: A Novel about Project Management by Tom DeMarco. The review presents a number of points leading to certain reasonable conclusions. While reading I tried to make notes and conclusions that are already known to many and are used as a reminder about the core principles stated by the author.</p>\r\n<p>I am pleased to offer these notes to you but I need to emphasise that, though being a poor substitute for the actual reading of the book, they can be of some use if you want to refresh your knowledge.</p>\r\n<p>So, here we go ...</p>\r\n<h2>Four Basic Rules of Management</h2>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li>Find the right people;</li>\r\n<li>Set them to work that they can do best;</li>\r\n<li>Remember about motivation issues;</li>\r\n<li>Put together a good team and encourage them to keep going in the same vein.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p>The rest is administrative nonsense.</p>\r\n<h2>Security and Change</h2>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li>If a person doesn&rsquo;t feel safe he or she will be reluctant to change;</li>\r\n<li>A manager needs changes to work successfully (surely, change is necessary in any other activity);</li>\r\n<li>Uncertainty provokes risk-avoiding behaviour;</li>\r\n<li>A person who avoids risks misses a zillion of opportunities and benefits that could have caused his or her life to change;</li>\r\n<li>It is nice and easy to bully a person with direct threats but there is an option of giving them to understand that they may be treated with callousness and cruelty exerting the same effect.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<h2>Negative Motivation</h2>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li>Threats provide the most unsuitable type of motivation if it is personal efficiency of your employees that you are hunting for.</li>\r\n<li>Whatever threats you make, the task will remain unaccomplished if you had allowed too little time for it from the very start.</li>\r\n<li>More than that, you will have to keep your promises in case people fail.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<h2>Parts of the Body Needed for Project Management</h2>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li>Leadership skills require heart, gut, soul and nose:</li>\r\n<li>That&rsquo;s why one should:\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>lead from the heart;</li>\r\n<li>trust to their gut;</li>\r\n<li>build soul into the team and into the project;</li>\r\n<li>have a nose for bullshit.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<h2>Commander in Chief on the Battlefield as a Metaphor for Project Management</h2>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li>The commander in chief&rsquo;s work has already been done before the battle begins.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<h2>Job Interview and Employment</h2>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li>In order to recruit a good employee a manager will need all their skills &ndash; heart, soul, nose, and gut (the latter to a greater extent).</li>\r\n<li>Don&rsquo;t try to employ staff single-handedly &ndash; it is much wiser to use intuition of two managers.</li>\r\n<li>Ask new team members to take on the tasks similar to those they had already succeeded in before and to think of their great ambition and professional advancement in terms of a project that will follow.</li>\r\n<li>Ask for a tip-off &ndash; your team members will most certainly be able to advise you on whom else to recruit.</li>\r\n<li>Listen more, speak less.</li>\r\n<li>All this is likely to work even better if you slightly stack the deck.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<h2>Productivity Improvement</h2>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li>There are no short-term measures that result in a rapid efficiency improvement.</li>\r\n<li>Productivity improvement is a consequence of a long lasting effort.</li>\r\n<li>Any efficiency improvement methods that promise an immediate effect are essentially snake oil.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<h2>Risk Management</h2>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li>Manage projects by managing their risks.</li>\r\n<li>Make a list of risks for each project.</li>\r\n<li>Determine those risks that cause a project to fail rather than final risks alone.</li>\r\n<li>Estimate the probability and cost of each risk.</li>\r\n<li>For each risk calculate an index, i.e. evidence indicating that the risk is turning into a problem.</li>\r\n<li>Put someone in charge of risk management one person who is not expected to maintain a Can-Do attitude.</li>\r\n<li>Establish available (perhaps anonymous) channels of communication for breaking bad news up the hierarchy.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<h2>Playing Defence</h2>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li>Cut your losses.</li>\r\n<li>You can improve your overall performance more by containing your failures than by optimising your success.</li>\r\n<li>Be aggressive about cancelling failed efforts early.</li>\r\n<li>Don&rsquo;t take chances on team building if you don&rsquo;t have to: seek out and use pre-formed teams.</li>\r\n<li>Keep good teams together (when they are willing) once the project is over to help your successors avoid problems of slow-building or non-building teams.</li>\r\n<li>Think of a formed team &ndash; ready and willing to take on a new effort &ndash; as one of the project deliverables.</li>\r\n<li>A day lost at the beginning of a project hurts just as much as a day lost at the end.</li>\r\n<li>There are one hundred and one ways to lose a day and none to bring one back.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<h2>Modelling and Simulation of the Development Process</h2>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li>Model your hunches about the processes that get work done.</li>\r\n<li>Use the models in peer interaction to communicate and refine thinking about how the process works.</li>\r\n<li>Use the models to simulate results.</li>\r\n<li>Tune the models against actual results.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<h2>Pathological Politics</h2>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li>You have to be willing to put your job on the line any day&hellip;</li>\r\n<li>&hellip; but that doesn&rsquo;t guarantee that pathological politics won&rsquo;t affect you.</li>\r\n<li>Pathological politics can crop up anywhere, even in the healthiest organisation.</li>\r\n<li>The defining characteristic of pathological politics is that  goals of personal power and influence come to override the natural goals of an organisation.</li>\r\n<li>This can happen even when the pathological goal is directly opposed to the organisational goal.</li>\r\n<li>Among the bad side effects of pathology: It becomes unsafe to have a leanly staffed project.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<h2>Metrics</h2>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li>Size every single project.</li>\r\n<li>Don&rsquo;t sweat the units &ndash; while you are waiting to achieve objective metrification, use subjective units.</li>\r\n<li>Form synthetic metrics from all the primitives (countable characteristics of the software) available to you.</li>\r\n<li>Collect archived data to derive productivity trends from now-ended projects.</li>\r\n<li>Tinker with the formulation for your synthetic metric until its values give the best correlation to effort for set projects in your archived database.</li>\r\n<li>Draw a trend line through your database, showing expected effort as a function of values of the synthetic metric.</li>\r\n<li>For each new project to be estimated, compute value of the synthetic metric and use it to pick off expected effort from the trend line.</li>\r\n<li>Use the noise level around the productivity trend as an indicator of what tolerance to apply to the projections.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<h2>Process and Process Improvement</h2>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li>Good process and continually improving process are admirable goals.</li>\r\n<li>There are also very natural goals: Good technical workers will focus on them whether you tell them to or not.</li>\r\n<li>Formal process improvement programmes cost time and money; a given process improvement effort may well set project work back. Evan if productivity gains materialise, they are unlikely to offset the time spent on process improvement for those projects that host the programme. A project can hope to gain enough from a single well-chosen method improvement to repay the time and money invested in the change.</li>\r\n<li>Projects cannot realistically hope to accommodate more that one method improvement over their duration.</li>\r\n<li>Multi-skill improvement programmes (e.g. increasing by an entire CMM level) are most likely to make projects finish later than they would have without the programme.</li>\r\n<li>The danger of standard process is that people will miss chances to take important shortcuts.</li>\r\n<li>Particularly on overstaffed projects, standard process will be observed rigorously as long as it generates sufficient work (useful or not) to keep everyone busy.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<h2>Changing the Way Work Gets Done</h2>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li>There is no way to get projects to perform substantially beyond the norm without making large reductions in the total amount of debugging time.</li>\r\n<li>High-performing projects spend proportionately far less of their time in debugging.</li>\r\n<li>High-performing projects spend proportionately far more of their time in design.</li>\r\n<li>You cannot get people to do anything different without caring for them and about them. To get them to change, you have to understand (appreciate) where they&rsquo;re coming from and why.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<h2>The Effects of Pressure</h2>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li>People under pressure do not think any faster.</li>\r\n<li>Extended overtime is a productivity reduction tactic.</li>\r\n<li>Short bursts of pressure and even overtime may be a useful tactic as they focus people and increase the sense that the work is important, but extended pressure is always a mistake.</li>\r\n<li>Perhaps managers make so much use of pressure because they do not know what else to do, or are daunted by how difficult the alternatives are.</li>\r\n<li>Terrible suspicion: The real reason for use of pressure and overtime may be to make everyone look better when the project fails.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<h2>The Angry Manager</h2>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li>Anger and contempt in management are contagious. When upper management is abusive, lower management mimics the same behaviour (much like abused children who go on to become abusive parents).</li>\r\n<li>Managerial contempt is supposed to act as a goad to get people to invest more in their performance.  It is the most frequent &ldquo;stick&rdquo; of carrot-and-stick management. But where is the evidence that contempt has ever caused anyone to perform better?</li>\r\n<li>A manager&rsquo;s use of contempt to goad workers is more a sign of the manager&rsquo;s inadequacy than of the workers&rsquo;.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<h2>Ambiguous Specification</h2>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li>Ambiguity in a specification is a sign of unresolved conflict among the various system stakeholders.</li>\r\n<li>A specification that doesn&rsquo;t contain a complete census of inputs and outputs is a nonstarter; it simply doesn&rsquo;t begin to specify.</li>\r\n<li>Nobody will tell you if a specification is lousy. People are inclined to blame themselves rather than it.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<h2>Conflict</h2>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li>Whenever there are multiple parties to a development effort, there are bound to be conflicting interests.</li>\r\n<li>The business of building and installing systems is particularly conflict-prone.</li>\r\n<li>Most system development organisations have poor conflict-resolution skills.</li>\r\n<li>Conflict deserves respect. Conflict is not a sign of unprofessional behaviour.</li>\r\n<li>Declare up front that everybody&rsquo;s win conditions will be respected. Make sure that win conditions are elicited at all levels.</li>\r\n<li>Negotiation is hard; mediation is easy.</li>\r\n<li>Arrange up front that when win conditions are mutually exclusive of partly so, the parties will be expected to move into mediation to resolve conflict.</li>\r\n<li>Remember: We are both on the same side; it is the problem that&rsquo;s on the other side.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<h2>Role of the Catalyst</h2>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li>There is such a thing as a catalytic personality. Such people contribute to projects by helping teams to form and join together, and to remain healthy and productive. Even if team catalysts did nothing else (they usually do a lot else), their catalytic role is important and valuable.</li>\r\n<li>Mediation is a special case of the catalytic role. Mediation is learnable with a small investment.</li>\r\n<li>The small ceremony beginning, &ldquo;My I help by trying to mediate for you?&rdquo; can be an essential first step in conflict resolution.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<h2>Human Error</h2>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li>It&rsquo;s not what you don&rsquo;t know that kills you,&hellip; it&rsquo;s what you know that isn&rsquo;t so.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<h2>Staff Level</h2>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li>Early overstaffing tends to force projects into shortcutting the key design activity (to give all those people something to do).</li>\r\n<li>When work is divided over a large staff prior to completion of design, the interfaces among people and among work groups are not minimised.</li>\r\n<li>This leads to increased interdependence, meeting time, rework, and frustration.</li>\r\n<li>Ideal staffing requires a small core team for most of the project, and then significant numbers of people added late in the process (as late as the last sixth of scheduled time).</li>\r\n<li>Awful suspicion: Projects that set out to achieve &lsquo;aggressive&rsquo; schedules probably take longer to complete than they would have if started with more reasonable schedules.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<h2>Project Sociology</h2>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li>Keep meetings small by making it safe for unessential people not to attend. A published agenda, rigorously followed, is the easiest way to make nonattendance safe.</li>\r\n<li>Projects have need for ceremony.</li>\r\n<li>Use ceremony to focus attention on project goals and ideals: small meetings, zero-defect work, etc.</li>\r\n<li>Take steps to protect people from managers&rsquo; abusive anger.</li>\r\n<li>Remember: at work Anger = Fear. Managers who inflict abusive, angry behaviour on their subordinates are almost always doing it because they are afraid.</li>\r\n<li>Observation: If everybody understands that Anger = Fear, anger will be a transparent signal that the angry person is afraid; since there is an inclination not to reveal fear, he or she won&rsquo;t be able to vent the anger anymore. (This doesn&rsquo;t solve the angry person&rsquo;s problem, but it sure can make it easier on everyone else).</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<h2>Pathological Politics (Again)</h2>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li>You cannot expect to cure pathology from beneath.</li>\r\n<li>Don&rsquo;t waste your time or jeopardise your position by trying.</li>\r\n<li>Sometimes, your only option is to bide your time, waiting for the problem to resolve itself, or for a good opportunity for you to move on.</li>\r\n<li>Miracles may happen (but don&rsquo;t count on them).</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<h2>Lean and Mean</h2>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li>Lean and Mean is a formula developed in failing companies by the people responsible for the failure.</li>\r\n<li>It is the opposite of any organisation&rsquo;s natural goal: to be prosperous and caring.</li>\r\n<li>Whenever you hear the phrase &ldquo;lean and mean&rdquo;, replace it with what it really connotes: failing and frightened.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<h2>Radical Common Sense</h2>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li>A project needs to have both goals and estimates.</li>\r\n<li>They should be different.</li>\r\n</ol>\";}'),
  (816,254,118,'3. Exploratory Testing: What is that and what’s it for?'),
  (817,254,119,'Evelina Tananaeva'),
  (818,254,120,'a:2:{s:5:\"tizer\";s:192:\"<p>This article touches upon one of the most interesting approaches to software testing which, I regret to say, is generally ignored by software testing engineers in their day-to-day work.</p>\";s:4:\"text\";s:4045:\"<h1>Exploratory Testing: What is that and what&rsquo;s it for?</h1>\r\n<p>Evelina Tananaeva, Leading Specialist in Mobile Application Testing at Qulix QA.</p>\r\n<p>This article touches upon one of the most interesting approaches to software testing which, I regret to say, is generally ignored by software testing engineers in their day-to-day work.</p>\r\n<div class=\"CenterImg\"><img width=\"418px\" height=\"345px\" src=\"/uploaded/image/imgs/cat.jpg\" /></div>\r\n<p>One of the distinct advantages I find in the profession of a software testing engineer is its being in many respects a creative type of occupation allowing its possessors to envision themselves as industrial or services sector specialists using various software applications for their professional needs.</p>\r\n<p>Having to deal with a bulk of software from different domains every day software testing specialists often face the following questions:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>How does one determine the scope of performed system tests and has maximum test coverage been ensured?</li>\r\n<li>Are specification-based test cases enough to maintain a high quality of the system?</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>Running a sequence of test cases day after day we gather that we are in fact confirming the already known information about the system rather than learning something new. The monotonous reiteration of our actions results in losing the living tension when running a software product, so that we divert our attention, relax vigilance and lose keenness of perception. As a consequence product quality goes down.</p>\r\n<p>What is the means to combat it? The answer is to try a different approach. A more living and more creative one. For example, an exploratory approach.</p>\r\n<p>Where do we start? First thing you have to put yourself in the shoes of an end-user who is seeing the app for the first time.</p>\r\n<p>In order to do it with maximum efficiency you need to have clear answers to the following questions:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Who are the target users for the system? (accounting managers, marketing specialists, bank clerks, insurance agents, etc.)</li>\r\n<li>What are their everyday tasks? For what purpose do they use the product?</li>\r\n<li>What typical tasks does the app have to do for the given target group?</li>\r\n<li>How does the product communicate its functions to the user? How does it provide cues?</li>\r\n<li>Is the app user-friendly? Is it fail-safe and secure?</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>Answering these questions will help in defining the scope of supposed tests. For example, when imagining yourself as an accounting manager, approach the task not as a software testing engineer who has to meet the specification but as an actual accountant preparing a quarterly or annual report, arranging for the payment, calculating the profit, and keeping accounts. Keep looking over the answers to the questions you defined for yourself when stating the purpose of the software product &ndash; this will help you stick to the point.</p>\r\n<p>In terms of this approach improvisation backed by experience and respective skills is likely to lead to amazing discoveries helping the app adapt to new risks.</p>\r\n<p>Ingenious exploratory testing can be considered one of the most important methods in software testing. However, its value is much underestimated and it is often discarded as loose and lacking a definite system.</p>\r\n<p>The progress continues supplementing the kit of existing tools and processes day by day. Yet tools and processes do not function by themselves &ndash; they require the power of human intellect. In other words, tools and processes merely help testing specialists in producing the needed result in terms of a quality testing process.</p>\r\n<p>Qulix QA testing specialists added a powerful thinking tool of exploratory testing to their wealth of knowledge long ago. In the course of testing we employ our creative potential 100% which has allowed us to devise certain methods of effective testing process management. You are hungry for quality software products? Then we are waiting for you!</p>\";}');
